In Neovim, "tabs" can be a bit confusing because they don't work exactly like tabs in a web browser. In Neovim, a tab is actually a collection of windows.

Here is the breakdown of the default commands and how to make them much faster.

1. Default Commands (The "Vanilla" Way)
If you haven't customized your configuration yet, use these commands in Normal Mode:

gt: Go to the next tab.

gT: Go to the previous tab.

{number}gt: Go to a specific tab by index (e.g., 2gt jumps to the second tab).

:tabn / :tabp: Command line versions for next and previous.

:tabclose: Close the current tab.

2. Recommended Keymaps
Most users find gt a bit clunky. Adding these to your init.lua makes switching feel much more fluid:

Lua
-- Use Alt + number to jump to tabs
for i = 1, 9 do
  vim.keymap.set('n', '<A-' .. i .. '>', i .. 'gt', { desc = 'Gap to tab ' .. i })
end

-- Use H and L (Shift + h/l) to cycle tabs
vim.keymap.set('n', 'H', ':tabprevious<CR>', { silent = true })
vim.keymap.set('n', 'L', ':tabnext<CR>', { silent = true })
3. Buffers vs. Tabs (Important!)
New users often use tabs when they actually want buffers.

Buffers: The actual files you have open.

Tabs: Layouts to organize those files.

If you are looking for that "VS Code style" bar at the top where every open file has a tab, you usually want a plugin like bufferline.nvim or barbar.nvim. These treat buffers as visual tabs.

Summary Table
Action	Command
Next Tab	gt
Previous Tab	gT
New Tab	:tabnew
Close Tab	:tabc
List Tabs	:tabs
