Ah, got it! In Neovim lingo, those are called Windows.

By default, moving between splits is a bit of a finger-stretcher because it requires the Ctrl + w prefix. Here are the keys you need right now and how to make them much better.

1. The Default Navigation
To move focus, press Ctrl + w, release, and then use a direction key:

Ctrl + w + h: Move Left

Ctrl + w + j: Move Down

Ctrl + w + k: Move Up

Ctrl + w + l: Move Right

Tip: You can also use Ctrl + w + w to simply cycle through all open windows.

2. The "Pro" Way (Better Keybinds)
Most Neovim users find the double-key combo annoying. You can map Ctrl + h/j/k/l to move directly between panes by adding this to your init.lua:

Lua
-- Move between windows using Ctrl + hjkl
vim.keymap.set('n', '<C-h>', '<C-w>h', { desc = 'Move focus to the left window' })
vim.keymap.set('n', '<C-j>', '<C-w>j', { desc = 'Move focus to the lower window' })
vim.keymap.set('n', '<C-k>', '<C-w>k', { desc = 'Move focus to the upper window' })
vim.keymap.set('n', '<C-l>', '<C-w>l', { desc = 'Move focus to the right window' })
3. Quick Window Management
Since you’re working with splits, these extra shortcuts will save you a lot of typing:

Action	Shortcut
Close current pane	Ctrl + w then q (or :q)
Make panes equal size	Ctrl + w then =
Max out height	Ctrl + w then _
Max out width	Ctrl + w then |
Rotate windows	Ctrl + w then r
4. Integration with Tmux?
If you use Tmux alongside Neovim, you’ll notice that Ctrl + hjkl works in Vim but stops at the edge of the terminal.

I highly recommend the plugin vim-tmux-navigation. it allows you to use the same hotkeys to move seamlessly from a Neovim pane directly into a Tmux pane as if they were the same program.

